KEY POINTS:

• Iterable → Root interface for traversing collections.
• Collection → Root interface of List, Set, and Queue.
• List → Ordered collection, allows duplicates.
• Set → Unordered collection, no duplicates.
• Queue → Used for processing elements in FIFO/Priority order.
• Map → Stores key-value pairs (not part of Collection hierarchy).

COMMON IMPLEMENTATIONS:

• ArrayList      → Fast random access
• LinkedList     → Fast insertion/deletion
• Vector         → Synchronized dynamic array
• Stack          → LIFO data structure
• HashSet        → Unique unordered elements
• LinkedHashSet  → Maintains insertion order
• TreeSet        → Sorted set
• PriorityQueue  → Priority-based queue
• ArrayDeque     → Double-ended queue
• HashMap        → Key-value storage, fast lookup
• LinkedHashMap  → Maintains insertion order
• TreeMap        → Sorted key-value pairs
• Hashtable      → Thread-safe map
• Properties     → Used for configuration properties

👉 ArrayList Code 

import java.util.*;

public class collections {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Generics Syntax : Supplying a class on the basis of parameters
        // Specifying this ArrayList of datatype Integers
        ArrayList<Integer> l1 = new ArrayList<>();
        // Methods on this ArrayList
        l1.add(6);  // adding element in the ArrayList
        l1.add(7);
        l1.add(8);
        System.out.println("After adding elements in ArrayList l1 : ");
        for(int i=0 ; i<l1.size() ; i++){       // to find the size of l1 using .size() operation.
            System.out.println(l1.get(i));      // to get the elements of ArrayList using .get() operation.
        }
        l1.add(2,5); // adding element at particular index
        System.out.println("After adding elements in mid of ArrayList l1 : ");
        for(int i=0 ; i<l1.size() ; i++){
            System.out.println(l1.get(i));
        }
        // Creating one more ArrayList
        ArrayList<Integer> l2 = new ArrayList<>();
        l2.add(49);
        l2.add(79);
        // Adding L2 in L1
        l1.addAll(3,l2);
        System.out.println("After adding elements of ArrayList l2 : ");
        for(int i=0 ; i<l1.size() ; i++){
            System.out.println(l1.get(i));
        }
        // Clearing complete list 
        // l1.clear();
    }
}

